                  </persName>
            .</p>
               <p>CHARLES FLANDERS. I <rs id="t18340904-220-viclabel1237" type="occupation">keep a beer shop</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-220-victim1313 t18340904-220-viclabel1237"></join> at <placeName id="t18340904-220-crimeloc1238">Melburn, in Cambridgeshire</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-220-crimeloc1238" type="placeName" value="Melburn, in Cambridgeshire"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18340904-220-crimeloc1238" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-220-off1235 t18340904-220-crimeloc1238"></join>, which is forty-two miles from town - I lost a gelding from my stables about eight o'clock on the night of the 20th of August - the prisoner was in my yard during that day - he worked in the neighbourhood as a <rs id="t18340904-220-deflabel1239" type="occupation">labourer</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18340904-220-defend1312 t18340904-220-deflabel1239"></join> - I suspected him, and came to town - I went to a constable, and at last met him in Old-street - I said, "Jem, you are the man I want" - he said, "Oh pray, oh pray forgive me" - I said, "It is out of my power" - I asked him where my horse was - it was a considerable time before he would tell me - at last he told me it was at his father's - his father is a chaff-cutter - I found the horse in his stable with another horse - I knew it to be mine.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. DOANE. Q. You went to his father's directly you came to town? A. No; not till I found him - I inquired for his father's residence - I have known the prisoner some years, and he knew me - he has never taken my horse before, to my knowledge - I lost it on Monday night, and found it on Tuesday evening - I traced him to town with it - I heard in the village that he had taken it- he did not tell me he intended to return it - I did not say, at the office, that I did not think he intended to steal it - I said I did not expect he would bring it back - I said I did not wish to hurt him - I do not recollect saying, that as I was in a passion, I gave him into custody - I will not swear it, but believe I did not say any such thing.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18340904-220-person1314">
                  JOHN 
                  WILLIAM WINTH
               <interp inst="t18340904-220-person1314" type="surname" value="WILLIAM WINTH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-220-person1314" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18340904-220-person1314" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable of Shoreditch. The prosecutor applied to me, and said the prisoner had taken his horse out of his stable, and desired me to go and look for it - he stated it to me as a case of felony - I said, "Do you mean to say he stole the horse?" - he said,"Certainly, what else could I mean?" - we met the prisoner in the street - the prosecutor said, "There is the man"- he caught hold of him, and said, "Jem, I want my horse, where is my horse?" - he did not answer - I took him into a shop - the prosecutor again began swearing, and said,"Where is my horse?" - he asked him to forgive him several times - we found the horse at the prisoner's father's stable, with another horse.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined. Q. He was walking near his father's house? A. Yes, within one hundred yards of it - he told the magistrate he had come to see his father and mother.</p>
               <p>CHARLES FLANDERS re-examined. My stable-door was not locked - I went out in the afternoon, and came home at eleven o'clock at night - the horse was gone - there is a door to the yard.</p>
               <p>
                  <rs id="t18340904-220-verdict1240" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18340904-220-verdict1240" type="verdictCategory" value="notGuilty"></interp>
               NOT GUILTY
            </rs>.</p>
